                        al-mawjūdāt</title>
                                          <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>The colour of the <material>paper</material> varies from cream
                           through coffee to several shades of green.</support>
                        <extent>256 folios <dimensions type="leaf" unit="cm">
                              <height>34.2</height>
                              <width>17.8</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="cm">
                              <height>27</height>
                              <width>12.3</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="modern">
                           <p>Pencil foliation throughout. As the pencil numbering includes three
                              fly-leaves at the beginning, what should be numbered folio 1 is
                              numbered 4 etc.</p>
                        </foliation>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="21" n="mistara"/>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink">Copied by <persName
                           xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied" key="person_f4041"> Shūmā
                              <foreign xml:id="per">شوما</foreign>
                        </persName>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="illustration">355 miniatures, which exemplify the mature
                        Isfahan style, maintain a high standard of execution throughout. An
                        extremely fine illuminated heading at the beginning of the text, with the
                        central medallion left unpainted.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <decoNote>Contemporary binding of black morocco with fine stamped gilt
                        medallions (flowers) and pendants (rabbits). Doublures of red leather, with
                        medallions and pendants of gold cut-out work on blue, green and red
                        backgrounds.</decoNote>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1632">Dated 12 Dhu'l-hijja
                        1041 AH (1632 CE).</origDate>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Colophon on folio 259a (256a according to the modern pencil numbering)
                        signed by Shamsa. At the beginning are two Persian seals with short
                        librarians' entries: 1. Pitifāt 'Alī Khān; 2. Mu'izz al-Dawla Bahādur Khān
                        (?), dated 1162/1749; one of the inscriptions appears to record the gift of
                        the manuscript from the first to the second.</p>
                     <p>Formerly part of the collection of the orientalist <persName 
                        type="standard"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/51695910" 
                        key="person_51695910">Antoine-Isaac Silvestre de Sacy (1758-1838).</persName> A label has been affixed to the
                        inside front cover which reads: 'M: Silvestre de Sacy, 226'. 
                        The manuscript then became part of the collection of the Persian scholar <persName
                           type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/#Bland,_Nathaniel,_1803-1865"
                           key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName>. Bland’s
                        oriental manuscripts were sold through Bernard Quaritch in 1866 to <persName
                           type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/#Crawford,_Alexander_Crawford_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1812-1880"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of
                        Crawford</persName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands, on behalf of the John Rylands Library,
                        in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName
                           type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/#Crawford,_James_Ludovic_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1847-1913"
                           key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                           Crawford</persName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
